    <section xml:id="projects">
        <title>Anatomy of a Project</title>
        <para>Define components of a project.</para>
        <para>What can be a project? Dev Guide, release notes, getting
            started guide, admin guide, other?</para>
        <para>anatomy of a pom file</para>
        <para>anatomy of a book</para>
        <para>generating output</para>
        <para>editing source files</para>
        <para>downloading source files</para>
        <para>tools</para>
        <para>A documentation project resides in a <emphasis
                role="italic">project directory</emphasis>, which you
            download from a git or subversion repository.</para>
        <para>The contents of that directory varies, but it always
            contains the following files and directories: <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para><emphasis role="bold">pom.xml
                            file</emphasis></para>
                    <para>Maven uses the POM (Project Object Model)
                        file to describe the project and to specify
                        what the goals of a build should be.</para>
                    <para>Maven (mvn) is the tool that you use to
                        build documents. </para>
                    <para>The goals of a build are specified as
                        &lt;goals&gt; in the POM file. Currently, we
                        have two possible goals, and generally use
                        both of them: a PDF file and an HTML (webhelp)
                        file. Here's what the &lt;goals&gt; clause
                        usually looks like:</para>
                    <programlisting>&lt;goals&gt;
    &lt;goal&gt;generate-pdf&lt;/goal&gt;
    &lt;goal&gt;generate-webhelp&lt;/goal&gt;
&lt;/goals&gt;</programlisting>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para><emphasis role="bold">src
                            directory</emphasis></para>
                    <para>Contains the resources directory, which
                        contains the source files and, potentially,
                        other files such as images and program
                        samples.</para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para><emphasis role="bold">target
                            directory</emphasis></para>
                    <para>Contains the docbkx directory, which
                        contains the products of the document
                        build.</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist></para>
    </section>




